ears since this pivotal shift in the academy, the university is moving away from “the people” in all their diversity. Today the university is refortifying its commitment to the defense of the status quo off campus and the regulation of students, faculty, and staff on campus. The progressive forms of knowledge that the student-led movements demanded and helped to produce are being attacked on every front. Not only is this a reactionary move against the social advances since the ’60s and ’70s—it is part of the larger threat of anti-intellectualism in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEducational equalizationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aKent State Shootings, Kent, Ohio, 1970. 0aMinoritiesxEducation (Higher)zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPublic universities and collegesxCurriculazUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRiotszMichiganzDetroit. 0aStudent movementszUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxCurriculazUnited StatesxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  a20th century protest.  aamerican studies.  acampus activism.  acollege student.  aethnic studies.  ahuman rights advocate.  aimmigration.  aindigenous people.  aintellectual landscape.  apoly sci student.  asocial movement.  astudent body leader.  asuccessful social movements.  awomens rights.  awomens studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029300740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096628440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966284/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles